<TITLE> Stocks up, turnover down as hype creates volatile market </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Feb 6 (bdnews24.com)The country's bourses closed up Wednesday on investor buying amid continued hype over state run oil companies Jamuna and Meghna. The day also witnessed a substantial decline in turnovers. The trading value of the two oil companies Wednesday stood at about Tk 436 million on the DSE and Tk 115.64 million on the CSE. Dhaka Stock Exchange's turnover plummeted to Tk 1.95 billion from Tuesday's Tk 3.72 billion, while on the Chittagong Stock Exchange slumped to Tk 404.58 million from Tk 658.63 million. Analysts cited the oil issues hype as the reason behind the market's instability, and said investors were rebalancing portfolios after market correction. DSE chief executive Salahuddin Ahmed Khan said that investors opting for oil companies was adding fuel to the market volatility. "Jamuna and Meghna topped the turnover board yesterday as well as today though the trading value declined a lot. This mood shift is inducing the market's volatility," the CEO said. Yaweer Sayeed, who manages over Tk 1 billion in funds for AIMS of Bangladesh, echoed the statement, adding that though investors were behaving abnormally the market was not. "Excluding the oil hype, the market's behaviour is quite acceptable, though the 'oil companies' thing is creating instability," he said. Dhaka Stocks started its day with a steep rise in the benchmark index. It however, stopped to rally after the first hour and remained more or less stable throughout the day before gaining a little bit towards the end of trading. DSE's benchmark DGEN or general index closed 22.03 points or 0.75 percent up at 2944.66. The DSI or all share price index ended on 2480.01, up 17.10 points or 0.69 percent. The bourse's blue chip DSE-20 also climbed 1.33 points, or 0.05 percent, to end at 2348.38. Gainers outnumbered losers 161 to 60 with some 19 scrips holding steady. The day's trading was paced by issues in oil, mutual fund, power and banks. Jamuna Oil topped the turnover board, ending 2.82 percent up at Tk 368.10. Meghna followed it to close at Tk 369.20, up 10.24 percent. Grameen Mutual Fund One eroded Tuesday's losses, ending 8.34 percent up at Tk 123.30. AIMS 1st Mutual Fund continued its rise from the previous day to close 5.49 percent up at Tk 9.98. Banking heavyweight BRAC Bank also continued to gain on declaration of dividends. It rose 0.31 percent to close at Tk 1442.75. Among the other scrips on the turnover board, AB Bank, Lanka Bangla Finance, S Alam Cold Rolled Steels and NBL also advanced. Summit Power fell. All the indices in the Chittagong Stock Exchange ended upbeat. The CSCX or selective categories index climbed 43.85 points, or 0.91 percent, to end on 4822.58. The CASPI or all share price index ended at 7503.79, up 64.48 points or 0.86 percent. The blue chip CSE-30 index rose 12.46 points, or 0.18 percent, to end at 6680.48. Of the traded issues 100 advanced, 32 declined and four remained unchanged. bdn
